title.narrative: MOST AT RISK YOUNG PEOPLE

description.narrative: By December 2016, most at risk young people are enabled to reduce their vulnerability through utilization of health, second chance education and protective services., which contributes to Adolescents And Hiv/Aids, Care And Treatment Of Children Affected By Hiv And Aids, Education â€“ General, Prevention And Response Services For Violence Against Children, Skills Development, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv, Violence, Exploitation And Abuse. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2016, 50 per cent of the most vulnerable adolescent boys and girls ages 10-18 in targeted communities are equipped with life skills, access quality healthcare services and contribute to decision making in their own communities.

title.narrative: Number of MARYP reached with individual or small group level interventions by age/sex/location and risk category

actual.value: 2016:Since the last update an estimated 700 adolescents and young people were reached through individual or small group level interventions including MSM, adolescent and young girls living with HIV, adolescent mothers and out of school adolescents and young people.

title.narrative: Number of policies and programmes revised or established in the protective services that prioritize most at risk young people

baseline.value: None for CP. Baseline assessments to be conducted in 2012

target.value: 2016:Programmes to meet the needs of most at risk young people are established within at least two protective services by 2014
